node.text:
The glorious Cotswold hotel @thyme.england was founded with an ethos of caring for and celebrating the land, an ethos expressed through its beautiful gardens, botanically inspired decoration, and seasonal cooking based around locally grown (often home-grown) produce. This summer (starting June 15) Thyme is staging its first exhibition in the estate's restored Tithe Barn – a celebration of the country meadow in pressed flowers by Brixton-based @jamjar_flowers. In time for the launch of the exhibition on June 15, the JamJar team have created a charming tutorial on how to press flowers especially for House & Garden.

Film by @frederickjewson
Thanks to @long_elgar

node.title: How to press flowers with JamJar and Thyme

node.text: March is the month when seed sowing starts in earnest, and our own @clarefostergardens has been preparing hers in her garden in Berkshire. In this video from her greenhouse, she talks us through how to sow seeds, discussing the the vegetables she's sowing, like chard and beetroot, and flowers like calendula and phlox.

node.title: How to sow seeds with our garden editor Clare Foster

Expect more from us over the coming weeks. For now we urge you to support @blklivesmatter and @blmuk, and keep the conversation about how we can change going forward.

node.text:
North Rode Manor in Cheshire is a place that rarely goes for long without rain, but for the garden designer @chrismoss.garden – who was brought up in Lancashire – the lushness of the countryside was a huge draw. Rectangles of box and uprights of yew, or pleached hornbeam – as well as the ever-expanding woodland – are the garden’s main feature, and here the flower garden planted mostly with texture and pale colours in mind. Follow the link in our profile to read the full story.
📸 @eva_nemeth

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by House & Garden Magazine in Somerset. May be an image of nature, the Cotswolds and tree.

node.text:
@farrowandball’s colour curator @joastudholme has applied her talents to her own 19th-century schoolhouse in rural Somerset, using carefully chosen hues in each room. The exterior of the house and its hillside setting is just as beautiful, with a Hadspen stone structure and a garden that looks out over the Somerset countryside. Follow the link in our profile to read the full story.
📸 @andreasvoneinsiedel

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by House & Garden Magazine in Dorset. May be an image of living room.

node.text:
‘It’s my version of a crisp, fresh take on country-house style,’ says @samanthatodhunterdesign, explaining the aesthetic she brought to this 16th-century farmhouse in Dorset. With views over the Stour Valley and plenty of charm in its bones, it was a dream project for Samantha to take on, helped by her harmonious working relationship with her clients. In the hall, chairs from Paolo Moschino for @nicholashaslamltd are paired with a ‘Scroll Bracket Console’ table and wall lights from @soanebritain. node.text:
The best interior design is always to do with the organisation of space. As Emma Burns, the designer behind this Kensington mansion flat says, 'No amount of decoration or picture hanging will make a difference unless you have the flow right. When she first saw this flat, 'it seemed so mean,' she says, explaining how it had been messed about and chopped up. Once she had corrected the layout, including that of the kitchen, she could turn to the decoration. The units in the kitchen (designed by Emma) are painted, along with the walls, in ‘Hardwick White', by @farrowandball, which gives the room a serene and timeless quality. Follow the link in our profile to see the full story.
📸 @alexanderjamesphoto

The owners of this Herefordshire farm, Charles O’Connor and Edward Greenall, have made gentle interventions to create a house that feels well established. The walls of this spare room are painted in @eb_naturalpaint's ‘Jonquil’; the bed is covered in an antique Welsh blanket with an old @colefaxandfowler fabric reused on the valance. At interior designer Susan Wyndham’s house in the mountains of southern Spain, where she has brought together furniture, lighting and fabrics from all over the world to create interiors with an exuberantly layered aesthetic. In the guest house (formerly the stables) a vintage lantern from Tangier hangs from the distinctive Mexican vaulted wooden ceiling, while sofas covered in @colefaxandfowler fabrics and bespoke lampshades made by @ashadeaboveuk, using Brigitte Singh fabrics, create an inviting place for visitors to relax. Follow the link in our profile to read the full story. 
📸 @capdemar

node.text:
Having bought a virgin plot in Palo Alto, its owners had planned on building a house in the Spanish Colonial Revival style, a look characteristic of the West Coast.  Interior designer @davidbentheim however, pushed for something with a distinctly more European flavour, and in the end his intervention proved decisive. Externally, the house - roofed in terracotta and painted in shimmering white - would not seem out of place in Palma or Ibiza. Indoors, the Mediterranean sensibility is stronger still. Follow the link in our profile to read the full story.
📸 @minh_ngoc | @houseandgardenuk

node.text:
A house that was once a collection of nine bedsits has been transformed by Natasha Howard, the designer behind Instagram's @philamena._, into an elegant and inviting family home. ‘It was a complete wreck, so we had to start from scratch,’ recalls Natasha, who worked alongside architectural practice @studio_mcleod for the renovation. In the open-plan kitchen dining area, the kitchen units are by @devolkitchens and are painted in the brand's cheerful 'Scullery Yellow'. The island is topped with a reclaimed laboratory worktop, while the bar stools are from @maison_drucker. Follow the link in our profile to see the full story.
📸 @horwoodphoto

node.text: Behind the unassuming exterior of his Australian home, Cameron Kimber has created surprising interiors that reflect his love of English country-house style. Cameron’s much-loved vintage printed fabrics and antique furniture are mixed with Chinese and English ceramics, lacquerwork and oil paintings. Follow the link in our profile to see more. 📸 @aliciataylorphotography

node.text:
Grounded in a respect for tradition and love of old buildings, designer @emma__ainscough has brought a refined playful spirit to her London flat, using her favourite colours and patterns throughout. In the bedroom, the headboard is covered in @bennisonuk’s 'Jungle Colors on Oyster' fabric, piped in linen by Hackney Draper. The walls are painted in 'Wedgwood Green' by @eico_paints. 'I love green - it’s made the room feel very calm. It's cool in the summer but cosy in winter.' Follow the link in our profile to see the full story.
📸 @lissiwaite

node.text:
The writer and garden-maker Umberto Pasti and his partner Stephan Janson, a French-born fashion designer and couturier, fell in love with Morocco more than 30 years ago. ‘We drove through the mountains towards Tangier and came across fields of irises as dramatic as an El Greco painting. It was raining and there was the most beautiful double rainbow.’ The gods were clearly pointing them towards Tangier, which in those days was like a ‘big village’, so they bought a house with some land not far from the city centre and Umberto began to make a garden there. He now has another house and garden in the countryside at Rohuna, both exquisite and filled with objects collected over a lifetime. Follow the link in our profile to read the full story.
📸 @minh_ngoc | @houseandgardenuk

node.text:
When Bianca Fincham and her family moved to Cornwall, they spent three years renovating a beautiful Georgian house by the sea, and then moved back to London, leaving a heavenly holiday rental, @pembrokelodge, behind them. "From the kitchen we can look out at the sea and see seals and boats bobbing around," says Bianca. "It’s beautiful even on a rainy day, with the water beating on the skylight. You feel that you’re outdoors, even when you’re not.” Follow the link in our story to see the rest of the interiors.
📸 @owengale
